## Error States

### 1. ErrorBoundary (JavaScript Errors)

**Component:** `ErrorBoundary.tsx`  
**Scope:** Entire page/route that throws an exception  
**Trigger:** Uncaught error in React component tree

#### Layout

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│             Something went wrong             │
│  We encountered an unexpected error.         │
│                                               │
│  [Error message — dev mode only]             │
│                                               │
│  [ Try again ]  [ Go Home ]                  │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

#### Props

```typescript
interface ErrorBoundaryProps {
  children: React.ReactNode;           // Components to protect
  fallback?: React.ReactNode;          // Custom fallback UI (optional)
}
```

#### Usage

```tsx
import { ErrorBoundary } from "@/components/ui/ErrorBoundary";

export default function DashboardPage() {
  return (
    <ErrorBoundary>
      <Dashboard />  {/* If Dashboard throws, ErrorBoundary catches */}
    </ErrorBoundary>
  );
}
```

#### States

| State | Display | Action |
|-------|---------|--------|
| **Normal** | Dashboard content renders | N/A |
| **Error Caught** | Error UI appears; children hidden | User clicks "Try again" to reset |
| **Development** | Includes error message + stack trace | Stack helps debugging |
| **Production** | Generic message; no technical details | User sees only hint to go home |

#### QA Test Cases

- ✅ **Happy path:** Component loads, renders children without error
- ✅ **Throw error in child:** Mock component that throws; verify fallback renders
- ✅ **Try again button:** Click reset; verify state clears and children re-render
- ✅ **Go Home button:** Redirects to `/`, checks navigation works
- ✅ **Dev mode:** Set NODE_ENV='development'; verify stack trace appears

